[2] Pakistan (Sindh province)
Date: Sun 22 Apr 2018
Source: Tribune [edited]
https://tribune.com.pk/story/1691954/1-measles-sweeps-sindh-26-children-hospitalised-dadu/


The measles virus claimed 2 more lives on [Fri 20 Apr 2018], while 26 children of a single tribe from Balochistan employed for the wheat harvest in Dadu district [Sindh] have been hospitalised. Official sources at Civil Hospital, Dadu said on [Sat 21 Apr 2018] that 3 of the 26 children are in critical condition.

The health authorities of Dadu were awakened to the situation on [Fri 20 Apr 2018] after the Baloch peasants staged a protest following the death of [a 1-year-old girl]. The local media [were told] that dozens of their children in their village of Duabo are displaying symptoms similar to those [the girl] displayed.

"We went to the local health authorities to request them to send a team to diagnose and treat our children but they didn't come until one of our children died," decried [a parent]. Dadu-based child protection unit in charge Naheed Qazi, who visited the village after media reports of the child's death, claimed that 8 children have so far died this year[2018] in the district while the contagion is relentlessly spreading. "The need is to fix responsibility on the doctors who in the 1st place failed to immunise the children against polio and those in the 2nd place who failed to provide the ill children timely medical treatment," she suggested.

A team of local doctors led by Dr Hameed Soomro and Allah Bux Korejo visited the village and shifted the 26 children to Civil Hospital, Dadu. The condition of 3 of the 26 children deteriorated on [Fri 20 Apr 2018] and the doctors suggested referring them to Peoples Medical University Hospital in Nawabshah [Sindh]. A total of 33 children sick with measles are admitted at the hospital.

Meanwhile, another child who was 18 months old, died in the Tando Adam town of Sanghar district [Sindh]. This is reportedly the 3rd death in the town in a week.

Earlier in January [2018], 6 children died within the span of a few days in Gorakh Town Colony in Johi taluka of Dadu district. The health authorities of Dadu had claimed that the officials or staff will face action if they were found negligent of duty in the inquiry. However, no action was taken despite the announcement.

Although measles-related deaths have been reported from all parts of Sindh, the virus has reportedly gripped the districts of upper Sindh more than those in the lower region of the province.

According to the World Health Organization's report, 5871 cases were reported in Pakistan in 2016. The figure almost doubled in 2017 to 10 540 cases. Laboratory tests confirmed that 2806 and 6437 cases were reported respectively during the 2 years.

Health practitioners point to incomplete coverage in the immunisation campaigns and a lack of efficient treatment facilities in rural areas as the cause of the virus's spread. 3 children died in Benazirabad district [Sindh] on 3 Mar 2018 and 5 were hospitalised after they were allegedly administered expired vials of anti-measles vaccinations.

[Byline: Z Ali]

