[4] Taiwan: alert
Date: Sun 22 Apr 2018 15:43 JST
Source: NHK World - Japan [edited]
https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180422_19/


Health authorities in Taiwan are on the alert as the number of patients with measles is at its highest level in 9 years.

The authorities say 22 people had tested positive for the highly infectious virus by [Sat 21 Apr 2018].

The virus is spreading among people who came into contact with a man in his 30s. His infection was confirmed during a visit to the southwestern Japanese prefecture of Okinawa last month [see Measles update (26): Europe, Pacific, Asia, USA 20180422.5761755 for a report on the outbreak in Okinawa, Japan].

At least 65 cases have been detected in Okinawa since the Taiwanese man's infection was discovered.

A flight attendant on board the plane with the man contracted the disease. Other patients in Taiwan include people who have travelled to Southeast Asia.

Taiwanese media report that about 5000 people may have come into contact with the measles patients.

Health officials say the number of cases is the highest since 2009, when 42 people were infected. They are urging people to see a doctor if they have symptoms.

Measles causes high fevers and rashes. It could be fatal for infants and toddlers and may result in miscarriages.

Japan's National Institute of Infectious Diseases says people will have immunity if they were vaccinated twice.

The institute is urging the public to check vaccination records as many people will be travelling during the spring holidays at the end of the month [April 2018].

